44
00:02:24,263 --> 00:02:25,713
[Door closes]

45
00:02:25,715 --> 00:02:27,715
How are you feeling this morning?

46
00:02:27,717 --> 00:02:30,885
I better get my sea legs soon.

47
00:02:30,887 --> 00:02:33,020
You ready to meet the crew?

48
00:02:34,690 --> 00:02:37,608
And what exactly is expected of me?

49
00:02:37,643 --> 00:02:40,110
Am I to make battle decisions?

50
00:02:40,146 --> 00:02:42,146
You'll be consulted on relevant matters,

51
00:02:42,198 --> 00:02:43,981
anything that falls
under the executive branch

52
00:02:44,033 --> 00:02:46,233
or anything pertaining
to national security...

53
00:02:46,235 --> 00:02:49,537
Which, given the circumstances,
touches about everything.

54
00:02:49,572 --> 00:02:53,073
<i>[Man speaks indistinctly</i>
<i>over P.A. in distance]</i>

55
00:02:54,076 --> 00:02:56,327
- He's not ready...
- Not yet, at least.

56
00:02:56,379 --> 00:02:58,329
He's come a long way in a short time, Sir.

57
00:02:58,381 --> 00:03:00,664
And I want you to get him
the rest of the way there.

58
00:03:00,716 --> 00:03:03,000
Be his guide, his preacher,
his father, his friend...

59
00:03:03,052 --> 00:03:05,252
- Whatever he needs.
- Aye, Sir.

60
00:03:07,590 --> 00:03:09,006
<i>Woman over radio: Kathy,</i>
<i>do you think I could borrow</i>

61
00:03:09,058 --> 00:03:10,591
<i>some condensed milk?</i>

62
00:03:10,593 --> 00:03:13,093
<i>Woman: Sounds like you're</i>
<i>making cheesecake again.</i>

63
00:03:13,095 --> 00:03:15,396
[Switch clicks] <i>Man:
At, uh, 30 degrees...</i>

64
00:03:15,431 --> 00:03:16,564
<i>Man: Hey, y'all.</i>

65
00:03:16,599 --> 00:03:18,899
<i>Does anybody have</i>
<i>extra diapers?</i>

66
00:03:18,935 --> 00:03:20,684
I can't believe how normal it all sounds,

67
00:03:20,736 --> 00:03:22,570
like a functioning community.

68
00:03:22,605 --> 00:03:25,105
Sounds like the president's intel's good.

69
00:03:25,107 --> 00:03:27,575
New Orleans may be the safe place to go.

70
00:03:27,610 --> 00:03:30,160
And there's been no word
about an immune army gathering.

71
00:03:30,196 --> 00:03:31,445
Nothing about immunes at all.

72
00:03:31,447 --> 00:03:33,113
Well, if they think we're listening,

73
00:03:33,115 --> 00:03:34,949
they might be communicating another way.

74
00:03:34,951 --> 00:03:38,919
Bullet missed all my major organs.

75
00:03:38,955 --> 00:03:41,288
Perhaps I have nine lives. Like a cat, no?

76
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:44,174
[Velcro rips] More like a cockroach.

77
00:03:45,378 --> 00:03:46,460
[Huffs]

78
00:03:46,512 --> 00:03:49,380
<i>[Indistinct P.A. announcement]</i>

79
00:03:49,432 --> 00:03:51,215
[Grunts]

80
00:03:53,886 --> 00:03:57,137
[Clears throat]

81
00:03:57,189 --> 00:03:58,472
Dr. Scott.

82
00:04:00,726 --> 00:04:03,227
- You wanted to see me.
- Yes.

83
00:04:03,279 --> 00:04:07,698
Well, I mean, it seems
congratulations are in order.

84
00:04:07,733 --> 00:04:09,400
You found a cure.

85
00:04:09,452 --> 00:04:12,361
Well, I'd by lying if
I said that it was easy.

86
00:04:12,481 --> 00:04:13,498
Well...

87
00:04:15,374 --> 00:04:18,492
And strictly scientifically speaking,

88
00:04:18,494 --> 00:04:20,578
I found your work to be rather impressive,

89
00:04:20,630 --> 00:04:24,715
the way you fused your D.N.A. to the virus.

90
00:04:24,750 --> 00:04:28,085
If nothing else...

91
00:04:28,137 --> 00:04:29,553
It was elegant.

92
00:04:29,589 --> 00:04:31,839
Thank you.

93
00:04:31,891 --> 00:04:33,974
It was never my intention to spread it.

94
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:35,559
It's important you know that.

95
00:04:37,396 --> 00:04:40,848
Niels, I've been working on this idea

96
00:04:40,850 --> 00:04:42,182
of nebulizing the cure,

97
00:04:42,184 --> 00:04:44,568
and I'm having a little bit of trouble,

98
00:04:44,604 --> 00:04:47,237
so I was just wondering

99
00:04:47,273 --> 00:04:50,274
if you'd be at all curious to...

100
00:04:50,326 --> 00:04:54,662
Take a look at my research.

101
00:04:57,500 --> 00:05:01,085
So you wanna hear about
the life of a gun for hire.

102
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:03,420
- Yeah. Capping oil Wells in Kuwait.
- Hmm.

103
00:05:03,456 --> 00:05:05,456
Babysitting third-world princes.

104
00:05:05,508 --> 00:05:08,008
- Tex: Wow.
- I mean, you even have a worst?

105
00:05:08,044 --> 00:05:11,977
- Oh, he was at Gitmo for 18 months.
- Ouch.

106
00:05:12,097 --> 00:05:13,597
Yeah, I got my stories
and the scars to prove it.

107
00:05:13,633 --> 00:05:15,182
Ah. Give me some of that.

108
00:05:15,217 --> 00:05:16,717
I'd show you, but there's a lady present.

109
00:05:16,769 --> 00:05:18,268
[Scoffs] Big talker.

110
00:05:18,304 --> 00:05:20,771
All right, sweetheart, what's
the worst you ever seen?

111
00:05:20,806 --> 00:05:22,389
You call me "sweetheart" again,

112
00:05:22,441 --> 00:05:23,891
I'll make you eat that pathetic
pair of 9s you're holding.

113
00:05:23,893 --> 00:05:26,060
- [Whistles]
- [Laughs] Oh, wow.

114
00:05:26,062 --> 00:05:27,561
You'll never know.

115
00:05:27,563 --> 00:05:28,562
No, no, no. Hang on.

116
00:05:28,614 --> 00:05:31,448
Answer his question. Worst story ever.

117
00:05:31,484 --> 00:05:35,903
What makes one war worse than another?

118
00:05:35,905 --> 00:05:38,822
Death is death.

119
00:05:38,874 --> 00:05:40,324
Bet you're a riot at parties.

120
00:05:40,376 --> 00:05:41,742
- Oh, don't even get her started.
- [Burk laughs]

121
00:05:41,794 --> 00:05:43,077
Raise you 5.

122
00:05:43,079 --> 00:05:45,963
Okay. We raise.

123
00:05:45,998 --> 00:05:48,749
What do you think, Burk?

124
00:05:48,801 --> 00:05:52,086
Do I have the goods? [Crunches]

125
00:05:53,889 --> 00:05:55,172
[Sighs]

126
00:05:55,224 --> 00:05:56,507
Niels: And what am I looking at here?

127
00:05:56,559 --> 00:06:01,178
This is the vaccine
compound before nebulization,

128
00:06:01,230 --> 00:06:03,397
and here it is

129
00:06:03,432 --> 00:06:05,149
after it's been sprayed into the air.

130
00:06:05,184 --> 00:06:06,433
Yeah, it falls apart.

131
00:06:06,485 --> 00:06:08,769
Have you tried reducing the particle size?

132
00:06:08,821 --> 00:06:10,437
I've considered it,

133
00:06:10,489 --> 00:06:12,606
but then it wouldn't be heavy
enough to drop into the lungs.

134
00:06:12,608 --> 00:06:15,325
And you're sure the physics are sound?

135
00:06:15,361 --> 00:06:19,113
Dr. Hunter worked it out.

136
00:06:19,165 --> 00:06:21,198
Julius Hunter.

137
00:06:21,250 --> 00:06:23,333
You must have heard of
him, from palm coast.

138
00:06:23,369 --> 00:06:27,621
Um, only by, uh, reputation.

139
00:06:29,125 --> 00:06:31,925
I've thought about
adding an extra component

140
00:06:31,961 --> 00:06:35,763
to the outer coat to prevent
the vaccine from drying out.

141
00:06:35,798 --> 00:06:37,181
Yeah, it would need to
be... [Exhales sharply]

142
00:06:37,216 --> 00:06:39,466
Particularly resilient.

143
00:06:39,468 --> 00:06:40,884
Precisely.

144
00:06:40,936 --> 00:06:42,770
Well, what about Anthrax, you know?

145
00:06:42,805 --> 00:06:46,356
It's strong enough to survive
for decades in any environment.

146
00:06:46,392 --> 00:06:50,277
One epidemic at a time, Niels.

147
00:06:50,312 --> 00:06:52,479
Right, right. Probably best.

148
00:06:52,531 --> 00:06:54,782
What we need is an environment

149
00:06:54,817 --> 00:06:57,701
that's been untouched by the pandemic

150
00:06:57,737 --> 00:06:59,119
and yet severe enough

151
00:06:59,155 --> 00:07:03,457
to promote adaptive activity in bacteria.

152
00:07:03,492 --> 00:07:05,542
How about water?

153
00:07:07,163 --> 00:07:10,164
That's just what I was thinking.

154
00:07:13,335 --> 00:07:14,551
Mussels?

155
00:07:14,587 --> 00:07:18,172
Freshwater mussels, to be exact.

156
00:07:18,174 --> 00:07:20,507
Mussels carry bacteria,

157
00:07:20,559 --> 00:07:23,010
and in order to survive harsh environments,

158
00:07:23,012 --> 00:07:24,261
the bacteria adapts.

159
00:07:24,313 --> 00:07:26,643
To do this, it protects itself

160
00:07:26,763 --> 00:07:29,506
with a sort of intracellular
suspended-animation chamber

161
00:07:29,626 --> 00:07:30,416
called spores.

162
00:07:30,536 --> 00:07:32,486
Now if I could get my hands
on some of those spores,

163
00:07:32,521 --> 00:07:35,522
I could add their proteins
to the outer coat of the cure,

164
00:07:35,574 --> 00:07:37,274
making it Hardy enough to survive

165
00:07:37,326 --> 00:07:39,326
the nebulization process.

166
00:07:39,361 --> 00:07:41,612
This is Niels' bright idea, right?

167
00:07:41,664 --> 00:07:42,696
No, it's mine, actually.

168
00:07:42,748 --> 00:07:45,332
I led him to it, and he... He played ball.

169
00:07:45,367 --> 00:07:47,835
So we find you a bunch of mussels,

170
00:07:47,870 --> 00:07:50,954
and you'll be able to aerosolize the cure?

171
00:07:51,006 --> 00:07:54,424
Not quite. I still need
Niels' stability sequence.

172
00:07:54,460 --> 00:07:56,960
- Which he hasn't given you.
- I haven't asked him yet.

173
00:07:57,012 --> 00:07:58,212
And if he doesn't give it up?

174
00:07:58,214 --> 00:08:00,214
Well, then I'll have to do it the slow way,

175
00:08:00,266 --> 00:08:02,466
by which time millions
more people will be dead.

176
00:08:02,518 --> 00:08:07,054
But for right now, I
really need those mussels.

177
00:08:08,808 --> 00:08:10,224
[Chandler sighs]

178
00:08:10,276 --> 00:08:14,144
So where exactly do we find them?

179
00:08:24,286 --> 00:08:26,002
The closest freshwater lake is here, Sir.

180
00:08:26,038 --> 00:08:28,121
St. Andrew bay, about a mile inland.

181
00:08:28,173 --> 00:08:30,757
Good. We'll get the mussels
and be back by sundown.

182
00:08:30,792 --> 00:08:32,676
I want this ship close to shore,

183
00:08:32,711 --> 00:08:35,011
somewhere the sub can't and won't dare go.

184
00:08:35,097 --> 00:08:37,797
O.O.D., recommend course 3-4-7.

185
00:08:37,849 --> 00:08:39,683
Alisha: Very well. Helm, right...

186
00:08:39,718 --> 00:08:41,017
T.A.O., bridge.

187
00:08:41,053 --> 00:08:42,302
[Ring] T.A.O.

188
00:08:42,354 --> 00:08:43,970
I want the all-clear for our landing party.

189
00:08:43,972 --> 00:08:45,889
Anything on subsurface search?

190
00:08:45,941 --> 00:08:47,474
Negative, Sir. All's quiet.

191
00:08:47,526 --> 00:08:48,514
We can support the landing party

192
00:08:48,634 --> 00:08:50,110
with the .50 cals and the 25-Mike-Mike.

193
00:08:50,145 --> 00:08:52,946
- CIWS is in air ready.
- Very well.

194
00:09:03,125 --> 00:09:06,493
[Indistinct conversations]

195
00:09:06,545 --> 00:09:08,161
Attention on deck!

196
00:09:10,048 --> 00:09:11,164
At ease.

197
00:09:11,216 --> 00:09:14,584
This is the finest messdecks afloat.

198
00:09:14,636 --> 00:09:17,387
If you can dream it up,
our chefs can whip it up.

199
00:09:17,422 --> 00:09:18,922
Mr. President.

200
00:09:18,974 --> 00:09:21,841
Bernie Cowley, culinary
specialist second class.

201
00:09:21,843 --> 00:09:24,394
I'm happy to prepare anything for you.

202
00:09:24,429 --> 00:09:27,430
Gosh, um, I don't know.

203
00:09:27,482 --> 00:09:28,815
What did you have for lunch?

204
00:09:28,850 --> 00:09:30,934
Oh, you don't want my diet, Mr. President.

205
00:09:30,986 --> 00:09:32,986
Nothing but grilled vegetables as of yet.

206
00:09:33,021 --> 00:09:35,272
But for you, name it.

207
00:09:36,491 --> 00:09:38,325
Well, uh, let me see.

208
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:39,359
Uh...

209
00:09:39,361 --> 00:09:42,362
I got prime rib, chicken cordon bleu.

210
00:09:42,364 --> 00:09:45,365
Well, it, uh, it all
sounds so... so very good.

211
00:09:45,367 --> 00:09:47,200
I just... I don't know where to start.

212
00:09:47,286 --> 00:09:49,703
Mr. President. Sorry to interrupt.

213
00:09:49,705 --> 00:09:51,288
Uh, Lieutenant Mejia, ship's navigator.

214
00:09:51,340 --> 00:09:53,089
We're honored to have you aboard, Sir.

215
00:09:53,125 --> 00:09:55,208
Just wanted to tell you
I'll do whatever I can

216
00:09:55,260 --> 00:09:57,377
to make this ride as smooth as possible.

217
00:09:57,379 --> 00:09:59,045
Well...

218
00:09:59,047 --> 00:10:01,715
Actually just came down here
to say hello to everyone.

219
00:10:01,717 --> 00:10:03,850
Um...

220
00:10:08,056 --> 00:10:11,191
I-I think we have to get to
that briefing now, don't we?

221
00:10:11,226 --> 00:10:13,393
Yes, Sir.

222
00:10:34,466 --> 00:10:37,133
I'm walking around a
ship full of 20-year-olds

223
00:10:37,169 --> 00:10:39,302
who know exactly what
they're doing at all times,

224
00:10:39,338 --> 00:10:42,005
on a mission to save a country
that's barely recognizable.

225
00:10:42,057 --> 00:10:43,757
And me, Mr. President,

226
00:10:43,759 --> 00:10:46,926
I can't figure out what to eat for lunch.

227
00:10:46,928 --> 00:10:49,929
Sir, how many people did
you have working under you

228
00:10:49,931 --> 00:10:52,182
when you were secretary of H.U.D?

229
00:10:52,234 --> 00:10:54,267
I know where this is going, Master Chief,

230
00:10:54,319 --> 00:10:56,269
but the last time I made a decision...

231
00:10:56,321 --> 00:10:59,906
The last time you made a
decision was yesterday, Sir,

232
00:10:59,941 --> 00:11:02,242
when you decided to move forward.

233
00:11:02,277 --> 00:11:04,327
And I'll tell you this...

234
00:11:04,363 --> 00:11:07,280
The Navy's been studying
leadership since 1775.

235
00:11:07,332 --> 00:11:10,033
Between the captain, the X.O., and myself,

236
00:11:10,085 --> 00:11:11,835
we have 67 years' experience.

237
00:11:11,870 --> 00:11:13,953
Leaders aren't born. They're made.

238
00:11:14,005 --> 00:11:17,791
And we all believe in you, Sir.

239
00:11:17,843 --> 00:11:19,959
Just give yourself time.

240
00:11:26,685 --> 00:11:28,268
[Exhales deeply]

241
00:11:28,303 --> 00:11:30,970
I'd like to have a plan as to how

242
00:11:30,972 --> 00:11:35,141
we'll engineer the spore
protein into the vaccine

243
00:11:35,143 --> 00:11:37,193
once the mussels arrive.

244
00:11:37,229 --> 00:11:39,729
I was thinking perhaps a stabilizer,

245
00:11:39,781 --> 00:11:41,981
very much like the one that you used

246
00:11:41,983 --> 00:11:43,700
to bind your D.N.A. to the virus.

247
00:11:43,735 --> 00:11:46,069
Ah. The real reason I'm here.

248
00:11:46,121 --> 00:11:49,289
You know that viruses don't
like to be tinkered with.

249
00:11:49,324 --> 00:11:52,075
They'll loop out any added foreign genes,

250
00:11:52,127 --> 00:11:53,493
and somehow, Niels,

251
00:11:53,545 --> 00:11:56,546
you managed to sidestep
the recombination process.

252
00:11:56,581 --> 00:11:59,883
Yeah, well, it was so long ago, you know,

253
00:11:59,918 --> 00:12:02,335
and I tried so many.

254
00:12:02,337 --> 00:12:05,338
I mean, honestly, Rachel,

255
00:12:05,390 --> 00:12:07,090
who can remember these things?

256
00:12:07,142 --> 00:12:09,509
You know that I took samples of your blood

257
00:12:09,511 --> 00:12:10,760
while you were recovering.

258
00:12:10,812 --> 00:12:12,011
You're not really gonna make me

259
00:12:12,013 --> 00:12:14,564
truffle this out myself, are you?

260
00:12:14,599 --> 00:12:18,101
Someone special?

261
00:12:20,856 --> 00:12:24,023
[Wheels clacking]

262
00:12:29,197 --> 00:12:31,030
No, not particularly.

263
00:12:31,082 --> 00:12:32,449
It's an old computer.

264
00:12:32,501 --> 00:12:34,868
Never got around to
changing the screen saver...

265
00:12:34,870 --> 00:12:37,370
He is a handsome fellow, no?

266
00:12:37,422 --> 00:12:40,039
So what I'm mostly
interested is the chiralit...

267
00:12:40,041 --> 00:12:42,008
Doesn't really seem like your type, though.

268
00:12:42,043 --> 00:12:45,261
Not much going on upstairs.

269
00:12:45,297 --> 00:12:48,548
I suspect that you tired of him quickly.

270
00:12:48,550 --> 00:12:51,468
You see, I remember this about you.

271
00:12:51,520 --> 00:12:54,471
Dr. Rachel Scott...

272
00:12:54,523 --> 00:12:58,725
Always the smartest person in the room,

273
00:12:58,727 --> 00:13:04,481
the unstoppable force in
search of her immovable object.

274
00:13:06,651 --> 00:13:09,319
Am I right?

275
00:13:21,666 --> 00:13:23,833
Danny: All right, perimeter sweep first.

276
00:13:23,885 --> 00:13:25,084
Check for survivors.

277
00:13:25,136 --> 00:13:26,419
Once the marina's secure,

278
00:13:26,471 --> 00:13:29,088
we look for keys to something with wheels.

279
00:13:39,901 --> 00:13:41,985
We got a runner!

280
00:14:05,877 --> 00:14:08,211
United States Navy!

281
00:14:08,263 --> 00:14:11,130
Come on out! I'm not gonna hurt you!

282
00:14:11,132 --> 00:14:13,266
[Door creaks]

283
00:14:23,895 --> 00:14:26,396
It's okay. You're okay.

284
00:14:26,448 --> 00:14:28,698
You can take off your mask. I'm not sick.

285
00:14:33,488 --> 00:14:34,988
Neither are we.

286
00:14:40,662 --> 00:14:44,163
Hey. Easy.

287
00:14:44,165 --> 00:14:45,715
All right, easy.

288
00:14:47,168 --> 00:14:48,668
Nobody has to die today.

289
00:14:48,670 --> 00:14:51,337
That's right. You're worth
more alive than dead, anyway.

290
00:14:53,975 --> 00:14:55,174
Hey!

291
00:14:55,176 --> 00:14:57,477
[Gunshot]

292
00:14:57,512 --> 00:14:59,262
Hold your fire! [Guns cocking]

293
00:14:59,314 --> 00:15:02,565
- Don't be stupid, kid.
- Ray! What do we do now?

294
00:15:05,854 --> 00:15:07,070
Ray.

295
00:15:07,105 --> 00:15:08,771
Put the guns down.

296
00:15:08,823 --> 00:15:10,740
Ray!

297
00:15:10,775 --> 00:15:12,692
Lower your weapons.

298
00:15:17,832 --> 00:15:20,249
Cruz: Come on. Back against the wall.

299
00:15:20,285 --> 00:15:23,169
[Weapons clatter] We're not gonna hurt you.

300
00:15:23,204 --> 00:15:25,204
What did you mean when you said

301
00:15:25,256 --> 00:15:27,707
we're worth more alive than dead?

302
00:15:34,624 --> 00:15:37,231
Wolf and Cruz went to the lake to
gather the mussels for Dr. Scott.

303
00:15:37,351 --> 00:15:38,460
They should be back soon.

304
00:15:38,806 --> 00:15:40,641
And they won't tell you who set the bounty?

305
00:15:40,693 --> 00:15:43,978
No, Sir. It's gotta be the immunes, right?

306
00:15:44,030 --> 00:15:47,281
[Sea birds calling]

307
00:15:49,919 --> 00:15:53,687
I understand you're the man.

308
00:15:55,925 --> 00:15:59,693
Tom Chandler, Captain,
<i>U.S.S. Nathan James.</i>

309
00:15:59,729 --> 00:16:02,546
Ray Diaz. Sophomore.

310
00:16:05,168 --> 00:16:07,918
What's this?

311
00:16:07,970 --> 00:16:09,670
It's what leaders give each other.

312
00:16:09,672 --> 00:16:14,008
You find yourself in a
Navy bar, and of legal age,

313
00:16:14,010 --> 00:16:16,477
that'll earn you a free drink.

314
00:16:16,512 --> 00:16:17,511
[Laughs]

315
00:16:17,563 --> 00:16:19,480
There's no Navy, no law, and no bars.

316
00:16:19,515 --> 00:16:22,683
Other than that, this
will really come in handy.

317
00:16:24,770 --> 00:16:26,820
Cut 'em loose.

318
00:16:29,692 --> 00:16:31,742
Let's you and I have a talk.

319
00:16:31,777 --> 00:16:33,244
[Click]

320
00:16:43,789 --> 00:16:46,707
[Door closes]

321
00:16:53,132 --> 00:16:55,516
These are good.

322
00:16:55,551 --> 00:16:57,518
You mind?

323
00:16:57,553 --> 00:17:00,387
[Dog barking in distance]

324
00:17:00,389 --> 00:17:02,523
My son's a huge comic book fan...

325
00:17:02,558 --> 00:17:04,892
Goes to conventions, whole nine yards.

326
00:17:04,944 --> 00:17:07,311
Not anymore.

327
00:17:11,234 --> 00:17:12,950
So what's his story?

328
00:17:12,985 --> 00:17:16,487
During the outbreak,

329
00:17:16,539 --> 00:17:19,073
he crashes his car trying to
save a town from the virus.

330
00:17:19,125 --> 00:17:22,076
Wakes up, realizes he has superpowers,

331
00:17:22,128 --> 00:17:24,745
but can't remember who he is.

332
00:17:24,747 --> 00:17:28,215
He uses his powers to help
stranded people get home,

333
00:17:28,251 --> 00:17:31,585
even though he can't go home himself.

334
00:17:39,595 --> 00:17:41,095
And where are your parents?

335
00:17:41,097 --> 00:17:42,680
Dead, we assume.

336
00:17:42,732 --> 00:17:47,518
We were at the summer camp up
the coast when the virus hit.

337
00:17:47,570 --> 00:17:50,688
[Scoffs] One by one, counselors bolted,

338
00:17:50,740 --> 00:17:52,489
trying to get to their own families.

339
00:17:52,525 --> 00:17:54,275
We stayed until we ran out of food,

340
00:17:54,277 --> 00:17:57,027
and no one ever came for us.

341
00:17:57,079 --> 00:17:59,280
And the bounty on my people?

342
00:18:02,418 --> 00:18:05,252
A few days ago, these
dudes in trucks showed up.

343
00:18:05,288 --> 00:18:07,288
- Were they American?
- Yeah, of course.

344
00:18:07,340 --> 00:18:08,839
They said, uh,

345
00:18:08,874 --> 00:18:11,625
the Navy was going
around offering the cure,

346
00:18:11,677 --> 00:18:14,795
and really they were injecting
people with the virus.

347
00:18:14,847 --> 00:18:17,464
- You believed 'em?
- Didn't surprise me.

348
00:18:17,466 --> 00:18:19,516
There's all kinds of
conspiracies going around...

349
00:18:19,552 --> 00:18:22,136
That the government was behind
the plague in the first place.

350
00:18:22,188 --> 00:18:24,138
Anyways, it doesn't matter what I believe.

351
00:18:24,140 --> 00:18:25,472
- They were offering food.
- And guns.

352
00:18:25,524 --> 00:18:27,975
Look, man, nothing against
you and your people,

353
00:18:28,027 --> 00:18:29,276
but I got mouths to feed.

354
00:18:29,312 --> 00:18:32,196
Well, there is no conspiracy,

355
00:18:32,231 --> 00:18:34,481
and we do have the cure.

356
00:18:34,483 --> 00:18:38,152
Matter of fact, we have enough
doses for every one of you.

357
00:18:38,154 --> 00:18:39,953
What I need from you

358
00:18:39,989 --> 00:18:42,323
is help finding these bounty hunters.

359
00:18:42,325 --> 00:18:43,624
If the cure is real,

360
00:18:43,659 --> 00:18:45,075
then what do these people have against you?

361
00:18:45,127 --> 00:18:47,961
They're a cult, naturally
immune to the virus.

362
00:18:47,997 --> 00:18:52,416
They see the cure as a
threat to their beliefs.

363
00:18:52,468 --> 00:18:54,668
If you help us,

364
00:18:54,670 --> 00:18:56,553
we'll bring you aboard our ship,

365
00:18:56,589 --> 00:18:59,840
find you a safer place to settle.

366
00:19:03,396 --> 00:19:06,897
[Sea birds calling]

367
00:19:06,932 --> 00:19:08,565
I mean, how do we know if
we can trust these guys?

368
00:19:08,601 --> 00:19:09,983
What else are we gonna do?

369
00:19:10,019 --> 00:19:11,352
Come on.

370
00:19:11,404 --> 00:19:13,687
[Indistinct arguing]

371
00:19:13,739 --> 00:19:18,409
Permission to speak freely, Captain?

372
00:19:19,779 --> 00:19:22,363
I don't like putting these
kids in the middle of our fight.

373
00:19:22,365 --> 00:19:24,948
They're already in the
middle of it, Lieutenant.

374
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:26,500
Immunes saw to that.

375
00:19:26,535 --> 00:19:28,585
Rest assured they'll be on
the ship and out of harm's way

376
00:19:28,621 --> 00:19:31,338
- as soon as possible.
- What about reprisals?

377
00:19:31,374 --> 00:19:33,173
We don't know how far
the immunes have spread.

378
00:19:33,209 --> 00:19:37,378
Dropping them somewhere else
now could be just as dangerous.

379
00:19:37,430 --> 00:19:39,129
We have the mussels, Captain.

380
00:19:39,181 --> 00:19:40,514
We should leave now

381
00:19:40,549 --> 00:19:42,800
before the immunes ever
find out we were here.

382
00:19:42,852 --> 00:19:45,386
We're over 300 Miles away
from their camp in Florida,

383
00:19:45,388 --> 00:19:47,388
and yet somehow their reach stretches here.

384
00:19:47,440 --> 00:19:49,640
We have to find out how they're doing this.

385
00:19:51,894 --> 00:19:53,894
It's a deal. You give us food and shelter,

386
00:19:53,896 --> 00:19:55,729
we'll give you the bounty hunters.

387
00:19:57,616 --> 00:19:58,816
Good.

388
00:19:58,868 --> 00:20:00,617
Only one condition.

389
00:20:00,653 --> 00:20:03,737
I stay and fight with you.

390
00:20:03,789 --> 00:20:05,038
Absolutely not.

391
00:20:05,074 --> 00:20:06,490
In six months,

392
00:20:06,542 --> 00:20:08,041
I'll be old enough to enlist
and fight alongside you.

393
00:20:08,077 --> 00:20:09,910
Besides, you can't do this without me.

394
00:20:09,912 --> 00:20:11,662
Nobody knows this place better than I do.

395
00:20:11,714 --> 00:20:13,247
And you still need me to tell you how

396
00:20:13,249 --> 00:20:14,748
to signal the bounty hunters.

397
00:20:20,222 --> 00:20:22,389
Give me the lay of the land.

398
00:20:35,427 --> 00:20:37,043
[Sea birds calling]

399
00:20:39,381 --> 00:20:41,598
How can she work with that creature?

400
00:20:41,633 --> 00:20:42,966
I can't even look at him

401
00:20:43,018 --> 00:20:45,685
without seeing my brother dead in my arms.

402
00:20:45,721 --> 00:20:48,471
I'm just praying he does something stupid

403
00:20:48,473 --> 00:20:49,739
so I can shoot him.

404
00:20:49,775 --> 00:20:52,108
So this is the spore sequence right here.

405
00:20:52,144 --> 00:20:55,028
Fascinating, isn't it?
The way it's regulated.

406
00:20:55,063 --> 00:20:58,481
This bacteria... when it
needs to turn into a spore,

407
00:20:58,483 --> 00:20:59,899
it uses D.N.A. scissors.

408
00:20:59,952 --> 00:21:01,318
D.N.A. scissors.

409
00:21:01,320 --> 00:21:03,903
Yeah, I've heard of this.
This is like a CRISPR system.

410
00:21:03,956 --> 00:21:05,155
Exactly.

411
00:21:05,207 --> 00:21:06,406
So we'll use this

412
00:21:06,458 --> 00:21:08,158
to add the spore protein into the vaccine.

413
00:21:08,210 --> 00:21:11,461
Of course, we'll still need
something to hold it in place.

414
00:21:11,496 --> 00:21:14,798
I don't remember the stability sequence.

415
00:21:14,833 --> 00:21:15,832
I don't.

416
00:21:15,834 --> 00:21:18,335
I told you, I wish I did. I don't.

417
00:21:18,387 --> 00:21:22,505
[Computer beeping]

418
00:21:25,510 --> 00:21:28,478
[Knock on door] Come in.

419
00:21:31,233 --> 00:21:32,849
You wanted to see me, Sir?

420
00:21:32,901 --> 00:21:35,185
I understand the mission
on land is going well.

421
00:21:35,187 --> 00:21:38,071
I may drop by the combat
center to watch for myself,

422
00:21:38,106 --> 00:21:39,272
if, uh, that's all right.

423
00:21:39,324 --> 00:21:41,074
Of course, Mr. President.

424
00:21:43,662 --> 00:21:45,028
Anything else, Sir?

425
00:21:45,030 --> 00:21:47,530
The intel you found at the White House...

426
00:21:47,582 --> 00:21:49,165
I'd like you to bring it to me,

427
00:21:49,201 --> 00:21:51,918
along with any debriefs
related to the immunes.

428
00:21:53,338 --> 00:21:56,423
Absolutely, Mr. President.

429
00:21:58,210 --> 00:22:00,293
[Crunches]

430
00:22:00,345 --> 00:22:02,962
[Door closes]

431
00:22:21,566 --> 00:22:23,450
All yours.

432
00:22:31,159 --> 00:22:33,910
That's the only road in.

433
00:22:33,962 --> 00:22:37,080
There's a perch right
there you can scout from.

434
00:22:37,082 --> 00:22:39,833
You'll see them long before they see you.

435
00:22:39,885 --> 00:22:42,135
Look, these guys are
packing some major firepower.

436
00:22:42,170 --> 00:22:43,670
They had guns I didn't know existed,

437
00:22:43,722 --> 00:22:44,921
and I play a lot of video games.

438
00:22:44,973 --> 00:22:46,756
Well, we don't have to worry about that.

439
00:22:46,758 --> 00:22:49,726
We're bringing a Navy ship to a gunfight.

440
00:22:49,761 --> 00:22:52,595
We need intel, which
means we'll need prisoners.

441
00:22:52,647 --> 00:22:54,597
Copy that.

442
00:23:02,074 --> 00:23:04,574
[Creaks]

443
00:23:05,944 --> 00:23:10,113
Hey, Tex, have you ever killed anyone?

444
00:23:12,667 --> 00:23:15,168
Yeah, I have.

445
00:23:15,203 --> 00:23:17,036
Cool. [Gun clacks]

446
00:23:17,089 --> 00:23:19,122
No, it isn't, squirt.

447
00:23:20,959 --> 00:23:22,208
Ask him, Jake.

448
00:23:22,260 --> 00:23:23,760
Yeah, I got it, Cody.

449
00:23:23,795 --> 00:23:26,262
Hey, uh, we were wondering,

450
00:23:26,298 --> 00:23:29,632
maybe you could ask the captain
if he'd let us stay and fight.

451
00:23:29,684 --> 00:23:32,268
He said yes to Ray.

452
00:23:33,638 --> 00:23:36,856
[Chuckles] Not a chance.

453
00:23:42,447 --> 00:23:45,732
[Whirring]

454
00:23:45,784 --> 00:23:47,650
Scat teams are manned and ready, Sir.

455
00:23:47,702 --> 00:23:49,152
- CIWS?
- Set to auto-fire on.

456
00:23:49,154 --> 00:23:50,904
What's the status of the RHIBs?

457
00:23:50,956 --> 00:23:53,206
Loading PAX now and
will notify when inbound.

458
00:23:53,241 --> 00:23:54,624
Music to my ears.

459
00:23:54,659 --> 00:23:56,842
Watch your step. Be careful.

460
00:23:56,962 --> 00:23:59,078
I got the rest of us
loaded up on the other boat.

461
00:23:59,131 --> 00:24:01,414
All right, thanks, Jake.
Everybody's accounted for.

462
00:24:01,466 --> 00:24:02,999
- Good to go.
- Good job.

463
00:24:04,719 --> 00:24:06,419
[Engine starts]

464
00:24:06,471 --> 00:24:08,505
Let's go.

465
00:24:08,507 --> 00:24:11,057
[Engine rumbling]

466
00:24:17,349 --> 00:24:18,765
[Squeaking]

467
00:24:18,817 --> 00:24:20,900
It's been three whole days.

468
00:24:20,936 --> 00:24:22,685
Niels' blood's been
coursing through their veins.

469
00:24:22,687 --> 00:24:24,020
How the hell are they still alive?

470
00:24:24,072 --> 00:24:26,072
The virus has to be somewhere in his body.

471
00:24:26,107 --> 00:24:28,191
He was using it to
poison those Teddy bears.

472
00:24:28,193 --> 00:24:31,110
The virus must have adjusted inside of him,

473
00:24:31,163 --> 00:24:34,197
migrated exclusively to his lungs.

474
00:24:34,199 --> 00:24:36,332
That's why he's so contagious.

475
00:24:36,368 --> 00:24:38,618
Probably happened months
ago, at the beginning.

476
00:24:38,670 --> 00:24:40,003
Then it's hiding out in there,

477
00:24:40,038 --> 00:24:41,788
below the radar of his immune system,

478
00:24:41,840 --> 00:24:43,506
along with his stability sequence.

479
00:24:43,542 --> 00:24:45,175
Which he may not even remember.

480
00:24:45,210 --> 00:24:48,711
Oh, he remembers. It's his
shining bloody achievement.

481
00:24:52,684 --> 00:24:54,634
[Knock on door]

482
00:24:54,686 --> 00:24:56,186
[Door opens]

483
00:25:00,809 --> 00:25:02,308
How are you feeling?

484
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:04,944
Uh, your doctor here thinks I need rest,

485
00:25:04,980 --> 00:25:08,231
but, uh, I'm actually
anxious to get back to work.

486
00:25:08,233 --> 00:25:09,616
[Sniffles]

487
00:25:09,651 --> 00:25:12,235
Can we have a moment?

488
00:25:14,573 --> 00:25:16,072
[Door closes]

489
00:25:16,074 --> 00:25:20,159
I've identified the conserved core sequence

490
00:25:20,212 --> 00:25:22,078
in your stabilizers.

491
00:25:22,080 --> 00:25:23,129
You have?

492
00:25:23,164 --> 00:25:25,415
I recognized the same 20-base pair

493
00:25:25,417 --> 00:25:26,883
on both sides of the virus.

494
00:25:26,918 --> 00:25:29,919
The odds of that happening
in nature, as we both know,

495
00:25:29,971 --> 00:25:31,721
are next to impossible.

496
00:25:31,756 --> 00:25:36,426
So, I took that as your
brilliant handiwork.

497
00:25:36,428 --> 00:25:38,094
[Chuckles]

498
00:25:38,146 --> 00:25:42,015
Well, you've eliminated a few
trillion possible combinations.

499
00:25:42,067 --> 00:25:44,017
[Chuckles]

500
00:25:45,320 --> 00:25:48,521
Can I ask you something?

501
00:25:48,573 --> 00:25:51,324
Yeah.

502
00:25:52,777 --> 00:25:55,778
I just think about what you went through,

503
00:25:55,780 --> 00:25:57,780
working to find the cure

504
00:25:57,832 --> 00:26:00,450
and fighting your own infection

505
00:26:00,452 --> 00:26:04,120
and the self-imposed
quarantine on the <i>Vyerni,</i>

506
00:26:04,172 --> 00:26:07,624
literally isolated, with no human contact,

507
00:26:07,626 --> 00:26:10,126
in this bubble, and...

508
00:26:11,596 --> 00:26:14,881
I guess what I'm asking is...

509
00:26:17,852 --> 00:26:19,552
Do you ever get lonely?

510
00:26:19,604 --> 00:26:22,388
Yeah.

511
00:26:22,440 --> 00:26:26,643
God, I know my situation
isn't nearly as difficult,

512
00:26:26,695 --> 00:26:29,145
but...

513
00:26:29,197 --> 00:26:33,066
There are sometimes on this ship...

514
00:26:33,118 --> 00:26:36,536
Well, no one who understands me and this...

515
00:26:36,571 --> 00:26:39,539
Unsolvable puzzle.

516
00:26:39,574 --> 00:26:43,876
And now, being...

517
00:26:43,912 --> 00:26:47,380
So close to the very mind that created it.

518
00:26:55,674 --> 00:26:57,974
Perhaps you were right.

519
00:26:59,678 --> 00:27:04,263
Perhaps my immovable object
is closer than I thought.

520
00:27:07,352 --> 00:27:08,901
[Exhales deeply]

521
00:27:11,189 --> 00:27:13,690
It's the three-prime end.

522
00:27:16,328 --> 00:27:17,860
Pardon?

523
00:27:18,913 --> 00:27:21,531
The, um, conserved core element you found,

524
00:27:21,583 --> 00:27:24,751
it's the very end of
the stabilizer sequence.

525
00:27:24,786 --> 00:27:28,037
You just go upstream from there,

526
00:27:28,039 --> 00:27:31,791
and the entire sequence is yours.

527
00:27:41,436 --> 00:27:43,302
[Exhales deeply]

528
00:27:43,355 --> 00:27:45,388
[Door closes]

529
00:27:47,859 --> 00:27:51,060
[Breathing heavily]

530
00:28:04,863 --> 00:28:06,279
Status report.

531
00:28:06,332 --> 00:28:07,948
Danny: Green's good to go.

532
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:10,283
Hired gun ready and waiting.

533
00:28:10,336 --> 00:28:12,285
- Taylor... rock and roll.
- Burk and Bivas, good to go.

534
00:28:12,338 --> 00:28:16,340
CIC standing by to support, Sir.

535
00:28:16,375 --> 00:28:18,342
All right, Ray.

536
00:28:18,377 --> 00:28:19,593
This is it.

537
00:28:19,628 --> 00:28:22,963
So how are you supposed to
signal the bounty hunters?

538
00:28:30,556 --> 00:28:32,556
- What the hell are you doing?!
- Come on, I hand this to you,

539
00:28:32,558 --> 00:28:34,441
I'm on the next ride back to your ship

540
00:28:34,476 --> 00:28:35,976
and you start the party without me.

541
00:28:36,028 --> 00:28:37,444
You can't bench me now.

542
00:28:37,479 --> 00:28:39,062
Watch me!

543
00:28:41,483 --> 00:28:44,234
Now, I don't plan to lose this fight,

544
00:28:44,236 --> 00:28:46,069
but this door opens, and it ain't me,

545
00:28:46,121 --> 00:28:48,038
tell those assholes you shot the flare

546
00:28:48,073 --> 00:28:49,573
and try to collect the bounty.

547
00:28:49,575 --> 00:28:51,158
Bad move, Ray.

548
00:28:53,545 --> 00:28:55,579
[Door rattling]

549
00:28:55,581 --> 00:28:57,247
Hey! Come on!

550
00:29:02,421 --> 00:29:03,587
[Panting]

551
00:29:03,639 --> 00:29:06,256
All teams be aware, Ray is still on land.

552
00:29:06,258 --> 00:29:08,175
I say again, Ray is still on land.

553
00:29:08,227 --> 00:29:10,227
He's locked in the trailer.

554
00:29:19,688 --> 00:29:22,572
[Static]

555
00:29:22,608 --> 00:29:26,026
Tex: Guests of honor are arriving.

556
00:29:28,614 --> 00:29:30,280
[Tires screech]

557
00:29:37,256 --> 00:29:39,623
[Rapid gunfire, men yelling]

558
00:29:43,929 --> 00:29:46,596
Come on, kids.

559
00:29:52,020 --> 00:29:53,470
Hey, where's Cody?

560
00:29:55,224 --> 00:29:56,473
He wanted to stay and fight.

561
00:29:56,525 --> 00:29:59,359
And you let him? You let him?!

562
00:29:59,394 --> 00:30:01,645
Captain, Cody wasn't on the RHIBs.

563
00:30:01,697 --> 00:30:04,731
- Jake covered for him.
- Chandler: I'm Oscar Mike.

564
00:30:04,783 --> 00:30:06,199
Gotta go find Cody.

565
00:30:17,296 --> 00:30:18,995
[Radio chatter]

566
00:30:18,997 --> 00:30:21,665
Captain is out of pocket. Keep an eye out.

567
00:30:21,667 --> 00:30:24,000
Can we get a fix on
them? Can we triangulate?

568
00:30:24,002 --> 00:30:26,336
[Bullets ricochet] Cody!

569
00:30:28,724 --> 00:30:32,392
Burk, I read two tangos
falling back up the road.

570
00:30:32,427 --> 00:30:35,061
Burk: We'll try to capture them alive!

571
00:30:35,097 --> 00:30:36,480
[Men shouting indistinctly]

572
00:30:36,515 --> 00:30:37,597
Cody!

573
00:30:37,649 --> 00:30:41,017
25 Mike-Mike has hostiles in range.

574
00:30:41,069 --> 00:30:42,769
Kara: Batteries release mount 2-5-2.

575
00:30:42,821 --> 00:30:44,988
Slattery: T.A.O., prepare
mount 5-1 for fire support.

576
00:30:45,023 --> 00:30:46,606
Kara: Aye, Sir.

577
00:30:46,658 --> 00:30:48,191
Cody!

578
00:30:55,701 --> 00:30:57,784
[Bullets ricochet]

579
00:30:57,836 --> 00:30:59,169
Uhh! [Thud]

580
00:30:59,204 --> 00:31:01,371
Wolf: Clear to move, Captain.

581
00:31:01,423 --> 00:31:04,424
Burk: Tangos captured. Copy that.

582
00:31:04,459 --> 00:31:05,926
[Men shouting indistinctly]

583
00:31:05,961 --> 00:31:08,545
Danny: Guys, I'm taking
heavy gunfire up here.

584
00:31:08,547 --> 00:31:10,547
Hostiles are 20 yards north of my whiskey.

585
00:31:10,599 --> 00:31:12,849
Give me a fire-control solution and engage.

586
00:31:12,885 --> 00:31:15,218
Kara: Cobra team, stand
by for one round inbound.

587
00:31:27,399 --> 00:31:31,735
[Gunfire continues]

588
00:31:31,737 --> 00:31:33,620
[Bullets ricocheting]

589
00:31:33,655 --> 00:31:36,289
[Exhales sharply] Can't find Cody anywhere.

590
00:31:36,325 --> 00:31:38,325
Burk: Look in the cannery.
That's his go-to spot.

591
00:31:38,377 --> 00:31:39,826
Kara: Surface, T.A.O.

592
00:31:39,878 --> 00:31:41,912
Adjust 10 yards east. Fire one round.

593
00:31:41,964 --> 00:31:44,247
[Whirs, blast]

594
00:31:53,258 --> 00:31:54,758
[Gunfire continues]

595
00:31:57,646 --> 00:32:01,147
Cody?

596
00:32:12,244 --> 00:32:15,829
[Door creaks]

597
00:32:28,961 --> 00:32:30,543
[Gun cocks]

598
00:32:30,596 --> 00:32:31,795
Gotcha.

599
00:32:31,847 --> 00:32:34,214
Bosses want you alive...

600
00:32:34,266 --> 00:32:36,516
Unless you put up a fight.

601
00:32:36,551 --> 00:32:38,802
Please?

602
00:32:38,804 --> 00:32:40,854
Put up a fight.

603
00:32:42,441 --> 00:32:45,859
[Click, squish] [Gasps]

604
00:32:45,894 --> 00:32:47,694
[Groans softly]

605
00:32:47,729 --> 00:32:48,945
[Gasps]

606
00:32:48,981 --> 00:32:50,730
[Groans]

607
00:32:50,782 --> 00:32:52,616
[Thud]

608
00:33:09,588 --> 00:33:12,337
[Radio static] Tex: Tangos neutralized.

609
00:33:12,338 --> 00:33:14,242
We have prisoners as requested.

610
00:33:14,806 --> 00:33:16,758
Repeat, tango is neutralized.

611
00:33:16,760 --> 00:33:18,427
[Static]

612
00:33:55,524 --> 00:33:57,149
Find what you were looking for?

613
00:33:59,028 --> 00:34:00,360
The mussels.

614
00:34:00,362 --> 00:34:03,530
Oh, y-yes. They were a tremendous help.

615
00:34:03,582 --> 00:34:04,615
Thank you.

616
00:34:04,667 --> 00:34:07,334
And I'm sorry to hear about the boy.

617
00:34:07,369 --> 00:34:10,204
And what about Niels?

618
00:34:10,206 --> 00:34:14,208
I think we're on the verge
of a real breakthrough.

619
00:34:14,210 --> 00:34:18,212
Well, then don't let me slow you down.

620
00:34:21,884 --> 00:34:25,435
Can't blame the captain
for what happened to Cody.

621
00:34:25,471 --> 00:34:27,387
I can't blame anyone. That's the point.

622
00:34:27,389 --> 00:34:28,856
- Hey.
- What?

623
00:34:28,891 --> 00:34:30,724
What do you want from me?

624
00:34:33,529 --> 00:34:35,863
Nothing.

625
00:34:35,898 --> 00:34:37,114
Never mind.

626
00:34:37,149 --> 00:34:39,233
Okay.

627
00:34:40,703 --> 00:34:43,320
[Clank]

628
00:34:44,740 --> 00:34:47,291
I was stationed in the
west bank for three years,

629
00:34:47,326 --> 00:34:50,744
another two in gaza. [Panting]

630
00:34:50,796 --> 00:34:53,830
Thought I'd seen everything.

631
00:34:55,084 --> 00:34:57,668
Then this pandemic broke out.

632
00:34:59,255 --> 00:35:00,587
And I thought,

633
00:35:00,589 --> 00:35:04,675
you know, maybe now we
have this common enemy.

634
00:35:04,727 --> 00:35:09,596
We even have this cure that
we want to give to people.

635
00:35:09,648 --> 00:35:14,434
Maybe, just maybe, we'll
stop killing each other.

636
00:35:16,405 --> 00:35:20,073
But nothing's changed.

637
00:35:20,109 --> 00:35:23,160
It's all the same.

638
00:35:27,666 --> 00:35:30,033
[Sighs]

639
00:35:30,085 --> 00:35:32,119
Chandler: We captured three immunes.

640
00:35:32,121 --> 00:35:33,787
They were all carrying these.

641
00:35:37,626 --> 00:35:39,676
You ever see any of
Ramsey's people use one?

642
00:35:39,712 --> 00:35:42,129
I didn't realize cell
towers were up and running.

643
00:35:42,181 --> 00:35:43,430
They're not, Mr. President.

644
00:35:43,465 --> 00:35:44,881
We haven't picked up a signal in months,

645
00:35:44,934 --> 00:35:47,801
and none of these phones
have a single call or text.

646
00:35:47,803 --> 00:35:50,520
But they were charged.
They're using them somehow.

647
00:35:50,556 --> 00:35:53,807
You said they were trying to
set up a communication network.

648
00:35:53,809 --> 00:35:56,560
- This must be it.
- Slattery: Our techs are on it.

649
00:35:56,612 --> 00:35:58,312
Meantime, we're gonna
lean on our prisoners,

650
00:35:58,364 --> 00:35:59,947
see what else we can get out of 'em.

651
00:36:02,067 --> 00:36:04,901
This is good work.

652
00:36:04,954 --> 00:36:08,538
But if we're gonna win
this war, we need a plan.

653
00:36:08,574 --> 00:36:10,824
First order of business...

654
00:36:10,876 --> 00:36:13,660
Show our fellow Americans
that we aren't the bad guys,

655
00:36:13,662 --> 00:36:15,996
despite the lies that
Sean Ramsey's spreading.

656
00:36:15,998 --> 00:36:18,915
Once in New Orleans, we
inoculate the survivors.

657
00:36:18,968 --> 00:36:22,252
We make it clear that the
American government is back

658
00:36:22,304 --> 00:36:24,221
and that we're on their side.

659
00:36:25,641 --> 00:36:30,427
The survivors most likely
are living offshore on boats.

660
00:36:30,479 --> 00:36:32,229
We need an evacuation plan

661
00:36:32,264 --> 00:36:34,648
in case the Ramseys are closing in.

662
00:36:34,683 --> 00:36:38,518
By now, those boats may have
exhausted their fuel supplies,

663
00:36:38,520 --> 00:36:42,356
so I suggest that we stockpile
fuel from local stations...

664
00:36:43,742 --> 00:36:46,994
[Helicopter blades whirring in distance]

665
00:36:57,456 --> 00:37:01,925
We got some intel on a
safe zone not far from here.

666
00:37:04,096 --> 00:37:08,765
Could be a good place for you
and your people to resettle.

667
00:37:08,801 --> 00:37:11,218
Helo's warming up.

668
00:37:11,220 --> 00:37:14,438
I was gonna check it out.

669
00:37:14,473 --> 00:37:16,723
Wanna take a ride?

670
00:37:23,565 --> 00:37:26,233
I knew Cody was amped up to join the fight.

671
00:37:26,285 --> 00:37:27,868
He never would have stayed behind

672
00:37:27,903 --> 00:37:29,903
if I'd gone along like you said.

673
00:37:33,325 --> 00:37:35,465
There's an old saying.

674
00:37:37,579 --> 00:37:41,915
"Anyone can hold the helm
when the sea is calm."

675
00:37:43,052 --> 00:37:47,587
Being a leader is not about being perfect.

676
00:37:47,639 --> 00:37:52,843
It's about weathering
the storm and carrying on.

677
00:38:02,438 --> 00:38:05,655
[Voice breaks] I just wanna go home.

678
00:38:05,691 --> 00:38:07,524
I know, son.

679
00:38:07,576 --> 00:38:10,994
[Inhales and exhales deeply]

680
00:38:11,029 --> 00:38:13,780
We all do.

681
00:38:13,782 --> 00:38:16,450
Feel better?

682
00:38:16,452 --> 00:38:18,285
Yes. Thank you.

683
00:38:18,287 --> 00:38:20,120
My arm was really bruising. [Chuckles]

684
00:38:20,122 --> 00:38:23,423
You know, there was much
times on the <i>Vyerni</i>

685
00:38:23,459 --> 00:38:26,543
when I thought about a moment like this.

686
00:38:27,963 --> 00:38:29,129
Did you?

687
00:38:29,181 --> 00:38:32,299
Well, I must admit, we're
quite a team, you and I.

688
00:38:32,351 --> 00:38:34,768
A team with cause for celebration.

689
00:38:34,803 --> 00:38:37,471
We solved our nebulizing problem.

690
00:38:37,473 --> 00:38:38,772
Yes. Well, I mean,

691
00:38:38,807 --> 00:38:41,274
we still need to find a factory somewhere

692
00:38:41,310 --> 00:38:43,276
we can mass-produce the powder.

693
00:38:43,312 --> 00:38:44,978
And we need planes, lots
of planes. [Rats squeaking]

694
00:38:44,980 --> 00:38:47,614
You know, I always wanted
to get my pilot's license.

695
00:38:47,649 --> 00:38:50,734
Actually, we don't have
need for any of that...

696
00:38:50,786 --> 00:38:52,953
No planes,

697
00:38:52,988 --> 00:38:54,154
no factories,

698
00:38:54,206 --> 00:38:55,622
no powder even.

699
00:38:55,657 --> 00:38:56,907
I don't understand.

700
00:38:56,959 --> 00:38:58,625
How do you want to spread the vaccine?

701
00:38:58,660 --> 00:39:00,627
Well, if you think about it,

702
00:39:00,662 --> 00:39:03,046
you were able to kill 5 billion people

703
00:39:03,081 --> 00:39:05,582
- simply by breathing.
- I...

704
00:39:05,634 --> 00:39:07,801
So the key to transmission lies within you.

705
00:39:07,836 --> 00:39:10,587
If I could teach healthy lungs

706
00:39:10,639 --> 00:39:12,973
to hold and reproduce the cure

707
00:39:13,008 --> 00:39:16,343
the same way yours do with the
virus, well, then I could...

708
00:39:16,345 --> 00:39:18,829
You could make the cure contagious.

709
00:39:18,949 --> 00:39:20,332
Of course, the trick would be

710
00:39:20,367 --> 00:39:22,334
understanding just how your body does it,

711
00:39:22,369 --> 00:39:24,753
to be able to compare
the D.N.A. sequence change

712
00:39:24,788 --> 00:39:26,371
between yours and the primordial.

713
00:39:26,423 --> 00:39:27,673
[Rats squeak]

714
00:39:27,708 --> 00:39:29,207
You have my blood samples.

715
00:39:29,209 --> 00:39:30,959
I do. [Sets down box]

716
00:39:31,011 --> 00:39:32,794
The problem is, is the virus.

717
00:39:32,846 --> 00:39:36,381
It resides exclusively in
your lungs, as we both know.

718
00:39:36,383 --> 00:39:38,550
That's the reason why it's so contagious.

719
00:39:38,602 --> 00:39:41,053
So, what do we do? You
wanna to take a biopsy?

720
00:39:41,105 --> 00:39:42,387
No. No, no. No.

721
00:39:42,439 --> 00:39:44,473
See, that wouldn't
work, because it's likely

722
00:39:44,525 --> 00:39:46,692
in the deepest recesses of your lungs,

723
00:39:46,727 --> 00:39:50,395
mixed in with thousands
of other innocuous viruses,

724
00:39:50,447 --> 00:39:52,981
so what I'm gonna need to do is

725
00:39:53,033 --> 00:39:55,400
just flush out the poisonous one.

726
00:39:56,419 --> 00:39:58,970
- Flush it out? How?
- Well, you remember

727
00:39:59,005 --> 00:40:01,422
those brilliant little D.N.A. scissors?

728
00:40:01,474 --> 00:40:04,127
Well, they're not only
capable of adding a gene.

729
00:40:04,247 --> 00:40:05,413
They can also remove one.

730
00:40:05,498 --> 00:40:08,332
So I'm gonna undo what you did.

731
00:40:08,368 --> 00:40:10,584
I'm gonna separate your gene

732
00:40:10,620 --> 00:40:14,672
from the virus inside your body.

733
00:40:14,707 --> 00:40:17,958
[Laughs] I'm sorry, but
that would never work.

734
00:40:18,011 --> 00:40:19,677
[Gloves snap] Well, yes, actually it will,

735
00:40:19,712 --> 00:40:22,713
if they have identical stability
sequences on either side,

736
00:40:22,715 --> 00:40:24,932
and...

737
00:40:24,967 --> 00:40:26,851
[Sighs deeply]

738
00:40:26,886 --> 00:40:29,970
You gave me yours.

739
00:40:30,023 --> 00:40:33,140
That would kill me.

740
00:40:33,192 --> 00:40:34,558
The gene would be liberated,

741
00:40:34,610 --> 00:40:36,894
and the virus would
explode out of your lungs

742
00:40:36,946 --> 00:40:38,696
and into the rest of your body,

743
00:40:38,731 --> 00:40:40,147
and, well...

744
00:40:40,199 --> 00:40:42,116
[Chuckles]

745
00:40:42,151 --> 00:40:44,869
There's just so much of it.

746
00:40:46,406 --> 00:40:48,572
If you think I would just allow you to...

747
00:40:48,574 --> 00:40:51,075
I mean, you are completely insane!

748
00:40:51,127 --> 00:40:53,961
I've already done it, Niels.

749
00:40:53,996 --> 00:40:57,415
The virus is doing its work as we speak.

750
00:41:07,060 --> 00:41:08,426
[Equipment clatters]

751
00:41:08,428 --> 00:41:09,760
[Niels grunting]

752
00:41:09,762 --> 00:41:11,178
O'Connor: What's going on in there?

753
00:41:11,230 --> 00:41:14,765
The people on this ship
will sleep better tonight,

754
00:41:14,817 --> 00:41:17,268
knowing that it died with you.

755
00:41:17,320 --> 00:41:18,769
Miller: Dr. Scott, are you all right?

756
00:41:18,771 --> 00:41:20,237
I helped you.

757
00:41:20,273 --> 00:41:21,906
Yes, you did.

758
00:41:25,495 --> 00:41:27,445
- Miller: Dr. Scott!
- You're gonna help all of us.

759
00:41:27,447 --> 00:41:28,946
[Gasping and gurgling]

760
00:41:31,834 --> 00:41:34,952
[Gasping]

